{
  "card_id": "wick",
  "type": "merged_concept",
  "canonical_term": "Wick",
  "aliases": [
    "candle wick",
    "Candle Wick",
    "shadow",
    "Shadow",
    "下影线/上影线",
    "影线"
  ],
  "school": "Price Action",
  "definition": "The upper or lower extension of a candle beyond its real body, representing price rejection/reversal. It forms from aggressive price movement and sharp rejection, leaving a tail. The 50% level of the wick (measured from body to extreme or from wick high to low) serves as a key reaction zone for directional bias, often used to anticipate continuations or failures.",
  "identification_rules": [
    "Identify a candle that shows an aggressive move in one direction followed by a sharp reversal, creating a pronounced tail beyond the body.",
    "Determine the wick's measurement: either from the candle's absolute high to absolute low (full range), or from the candle body to the wick's extreme (tail only), depending on context. Mark the 50% level of that range as the key equilibrium/reaction zone.",
    "For a bullish wick (lower tail), the upper half of the wick (from 50% to the body) is expected to act as support for further upside.",
    "For a bearish wick (upper tail), the lower half of the wick (from 50% to the body) is expected to act as support for further downside.",
    "A wick is considered respected when the next candle opens, trades within the designated half, and expands in the intended direction without closing through the 50% level.",
    "A wick is disrespected when price closes through the 50% level, suggesting price will instead target the wick's extreme.",
    "Apply the same wick equilibrium/respect rules fractally across multiple time frames.",
    "A candle qualifies as having a 'large wick' when the wick is disproportionately larger than the body, commonly after price closes back through the 0.5 level of the prior candle's range.",
    "In low time frames (e.g., 5min, 1hr), identify wicks where price opens, moves quickly in one direction (forming the wick), then closes in the opposite direction."
  ],
  "trading_implication": "Wicks define directional bias: respect of the 50% level indicates continuation in the direction of the reversal, offering entry for at least 2R. Disrespect signals price will take out the extreme. Use the wick's midpoint to locate reactions, change-in-state-of-delivery zones, and PD array alignment. Best confirmed with higher time frame context and sweeps of previous day high/low.",
  "common_mistakes": [
    "Over-relying on the 0.5 level as absolute support/resistance, ignoring market structure and higher time frame context.",
    "Using 0.5 of the full candle range when a large wick warrants using only the wick's range.",
    "Marking the 50% level from incorrect reference points (e.g., body to body, or not using the appropriate measurement for the context).",
    "Expecting deep retracements into the opposite half of the wick during expansion, when price typically respects only the near half.",
    "Forcing a reversal trade after price closes through the 50% of the wick, ignoring the disrespect signal.",
    "Ignoring broader context (e.g., consolidation) that lowers wick respect probability.",
    "Expecting perfect respect every time without lower time frame confirmation.",
    "Confusing wicks with other patterns (e.g., FVG, OB) leading to incorrect support/resistance judgments."
  ],
